            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the scaffolding load calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates the
                <strong>maximum safe working load</strong> for a single scaffold
                bay and platform based on:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Scaffold duty rating (light, medium, heavy, or custom design
                  load)
                </li>
                <li>Bay length (span between supports)</li>
                <li>Platform width and number of planks</li>
                <li>Allowable load per plank at the given span</li>
                <li>Number of loaded levels</li>
                <li>Chosen safety factor on the working load</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It compares the <strong>design platform load</strong> from the
                duty rating with the <strong>plank capacity</strong> and reports
                the <strong>governing safe load</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>Step 1 – Platform area</h3>
              <p>The platform area for one bay is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Imperial:</strong> \( A = L_{\text{bay}} \times
                  W_{\text{platform}} \) (ft²)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Metric:</strong> \( A = L_{\text{bay}} \times
                  W_{\text{platform}} \) (m²)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 2 – Design platform load from duty rating</h3>
              <p>
                For light, medium, and heavy duty scaffolds, OSHA and many
                manufacturers use typical
                <strong>uniformly distributed loads (UDL)</strong> on the
                platform:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Light duty:</strong> ≈ 25 lb/ft² (1.2 kN/m²)</li>
                <li><strong>Medium duty:</strong> ≈ 50 lb/ft² (2.4 kN/m²)</li>
                <li><strong>Heavy duty:</strong> ≈ 75 lb/ft² (3.6 kN/m²)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The total design load on one platform is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( W_{\text{design, platform}} = q_{\text{duty}} \times A \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 3 – Plank capacity</h3>
              <p>
                Each plank has a rated capacity at a given span (from
                manufacturer tables or standards). The total plank capacity for
                one platform is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( W_{\text{planks}} = n_{\text{planks}} \times
                  W_{\text{plank, allowable}} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator assumes all planks share the load equally and
                that the plank rating already includes the manufacturer’s safety
                factor.
              </p>

              <h3>Step 4 – Governing capacity and safety factor</h3>
              <p>
                The governing capacity per platform is the
                <strong>minimum</strong> of the design platform load and the
                total plank capacity:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( W_{\text{governing, platform}} = \min\left(
                  W_{\text{design, platform}},\; W_{\text{planks}} \right) \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                To get a <strong>safe working load</strong>, we divide by the
                chosen safety factor:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( W_{\text{safe, platform}} = \dfrac{W_{\text{governing,
                  platform}}}{\gamma_{\text{safety}}} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For multiple loaded levels in the same bay, the total safe
                working load per bay is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( W_{\text{safe, bay}} = W_{\text{safe, platform}} \times
                  n_{\text{levels}} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 5 – Load concentration on one bay</h3>
              <p>
                Real scaffolds rarely have perfectly uniform loads. Workers,
                materials, and equipment often concentrate on a single bay. The
                <em>load share</em> input lets you assume that a certain
                percentage of the total live load is carried by the bay you are
                checking.
              </p>
              <p>
                For a conservative check, use <strong>100%</strong> (all load on
                one bay). For long runs with many bays and evenly distributed
                materials, you might justify a lower percentage, but this should
                be done by a competent person or engineer.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Suppose you have:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Medium duty scaffold (50 lb/ft²)</li>
                <li>Bay length = 7 ft</li>
                <li>Platform width = 5 ft</li>
                <li>3 planks, each rated 500 lb at 7 ft span</li>
                <li>1 loaded level</li>
                <li>Safety factor = 2.0</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Area \( A = 7 \times 5 = 35 \,\text{ft}^2 \)</li>
                <li>
                  Design platform load \( W_{\text{design}} = 50 \times 35 =
                  1750 \,\text{lb} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Plank capacity \( W_{\text{planks}} = 3 \times 500 = 1500
                  \,\text{lb} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Governing capacity \( = \min(1750, 1500) = 1500 \,\text{lb} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Safe working load per platform \( = 1500 / 2.0 = 750
                  \,\text{lb} \)
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                So this configuration would be limited to about
                <strong>750 lb</strong> of live load on that platform, assuming
                the frames, braces, and connections are at least as strong and
                all other code requirements are met.
              </p>

              <h2>OSHA scaffold load requirements (summary)</h2>
              <p>
                In the United States, OSHA 29 CFR 1926.451 requires that
                scaffolds and their components:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Support, without failure, at least
                  <strong>4 times</strong> the maximum intended load
                </li>
                <li>
                  Be designed by a qualified person and constructed/loaded under
                  a competent person’s supervision
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use planks and platforms that meet specific deflection and
                  capacity limits
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Suspension scaffolds have even higher factors (typically 6×).
                Other jurisdictions (e.g., EN 12811 in Europe) have similar but
                not identical requirements.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations of this scaffolding load calculator</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes simple bay geometry and uniformly distributed loads.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not check frame, brace, tie, or foundation capacities.
                </li>
                <li>Does not consider wind, impact, or seismic loads.</li>
                <li>
                  Does not verify deflection limits or stability (overturning,
                  sliding).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always treat the results as a <strong>screening tool</strong>.
                For real projects, use manufacturer design guides and have
                critical scaffolds checked by a qualified engineer.
              </p>

              <h2>Best practices for safe scaffold loading</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Never exceed the manufacturer’s maximum intended load or duty
                  rating.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Keep heavy materials close to standards (posts), not at
                  midspan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Distribute materials across multiple bays where possible.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Do not remove braces or ties to “make room” for materials.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Inspect planks regularly for damage, rot, or excessive
                  deflection.
                </li>
